<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"  xml:id="ch_recursion_induction">
  <title>Recursion and Induction</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this chapter,
      we introduce a fundamental idea of discrete mathematics and computer science:
      recursion.
      Essentially,
      recursion is a problem-solving strategy in which we replace the problem we are trying to solve with a smaller,
      hopefully easier, version of the same problem.
      We continue this replacement with smaller and smaller versions of the problem until we eventually reach a version of the problem that is small enough to know the answer.
    </p>
    <p>
      We start our exploration of recursions by looking at recursively-defined sequences in <xref ref="sec_recursively_defined_sequences"></xref>.
      Next, in <xref ref="sec_math_ind"></xref>,
      we introduce proof by mathematical induction,
      a proof format that is particularly useful for verifying that recursively-defined structures have explicit properties.
      <xref ref="sec_matrix">In</xref>,
      we take a brief excursion to visit matrices and finite groups,
      which also gives us the opportunity to practice proofs by mathematical induction.
      <xref ref="sec_fibonacci_higher"></xref>
      we explore the Fibonacci sequence and other examples of higher order recursions and introduce an extension of proof by mathematical induction.
      Last, we investigate other recursively-defined structures,
      including sets and graphs,
      and how to count with recursions in <xref ref="sec_rec_def_structures"></xref>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <xi:include  href="sec_recursively_defined_sequences.ptx"/>
  <xi:include  href="sec_math_ind.ptx"/>
